[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A *derivation* of a string for a grammar is a sequence of grammar rule applications that transform the start symbol into the string.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A derivation proves that the string belongs to the grammar's language.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] For clarity, the intermediate string is usually given as well.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Given such a strategy, a derivation is completely determined by the sequence of rules applied.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The distinction between leftmost derivation and rightmost derivation is important because in most parsers the transformation of the input is defined by giving a piece of code for every grammar rule that is executed whenever the rule is applied.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Therefore, it is important to know whether the parser determines a leftmost or a rightmost derivation because this determines the order in which the pieces of code will be executed.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] See for an example LL parsers and LR parsers.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A derivation also imposes in some sense a hierarchical structure on the string that is derived.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] where {...}*S* denotes a substring recognized as belonging to *S*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] This tree is called a *parse tree* or "concrete syntax tree" of the string, by contrast with the abstract syntax tree.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Note however that both parse trees can be obtained by both leftmost and rightmost derivations.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] If a string in the language of the grammar has more than one parsing tree, then the grammar is said to be an *ambiguous grammar*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Such grammars are usually hard to parse because the parser cannot always decide which grammar rule it has to apply.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Usually, ambiguity is a feature of the grammar, not the language, and an unambiguous grammar can be found that generates the same context-free language.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] However, there are certain languages that can only be generated by ambiguous grammars; such languages are called *inherently ambiguous languages*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Every context-free grammar with no ε-production has an equivalent grammar in Chomsky normal form, and a grammar in Greibach normal form.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] "Equivalent" here means that the two grammars generate the same language.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The especially simple form of production rules in Chomsky normal form grammars has both theoretical and practical implications.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] For instance, given a context-free grammar, one can use the Chomsky normal form to construct a polynomial-time algorithm that decides whether a given string is in the language represented by that grammar or not (the CYK algorithm).
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] They are not closed under general intersection (hence neither under complementation) and set difference.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The following are some decidable problems about context-free grammars.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Context-free parsing for Chomsky normal form grammars was shown by Leslie G.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Valiant to be reducible to Boolean matrix multiplication, thus inheriting its complexity upper bound of *O*(*n*2.3728639).
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Conversely, Lillian Lee has shown *O*(*n*3−*ε*) Boolean matrix multiplication to be reducible to *O*(*n*3−3*ε*) CFG parsing, thus establishing some kind of lower bound for the latter.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A nonterminal symbol X is called *productive*, or *generating*, if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~w$ for some string w of terminal symbols.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] X is called *reachable* if there is a derivation $S~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\alpha X\beta$ for some strings $\alpha ,\beta$ of nonterminal and terminal symbols from the start symbol.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] X is called *useless* if it is unreachable or unproductive.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] X is called *nullable* if there is a derivation $X~{\stackrel {*}{\Rightarrow }}~\varepsilon$ .
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A rule $X\rightarrow \varepsilon$ is called an *ε-production*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A derivation $X~{\stackrel {+}{\Rightarrow }}~X$ is called a *cycle*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] In particular, an alternative containing a useless nonterminal symbol can be deleted from the right-hand side of a rule.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Such rules and alternatives are called *useless*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] In the depicted example grammar, the nonterminal *D* is unreachable, and *E* is unproductive, while *C* → *C* causes a cycle.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Hence, omitting the last three rules does not change the language generated by the grammar, nor does omitting the alternatives "| *C*c | *E*e" from the right-hand side of the rule for *S*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A context-free grammar is said to be *proper* if it has neither useless symbols nor ε-productions nor cycles.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Combining the above algorithms, every context-free grammar not generating ε can be transformed into a weakly equivalent proper one.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] It is decidable whether a given *grammar* is a regular grammar, as well as whether it is an LL(*k*) grammar for a given *k* ≥ 0.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] If *k* is not given, the latter problem is undecidable.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Given a context-free grammar, it is not decidable whether its language is regular, nor whether it is an LL(*k*) language for a given *k*.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] There are algorithms to decide whether the language of a given context-free grammar is empty, as well as whether it is finite.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Some questions that are undecidable for wider classes of grammars become decidable for context-free grammars; e.g. the emptiness problem (whether the grammar generates any terminal strings at all), is undecidable for context-sensitive grammars, but decidable for context-free grammars.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] However, many problems are undecidable even for context-free grammars; the most prominent ones are handled in the following.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Given a CFG, does it generate the language of all strings over the alphabet of terminal symbols used in its rules?
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A reduction can be demonstrated to this problem from the well-known undecidable problem of determining whether a Turing machine accepts a particular input (the halting problem).
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The reduction uses the concept of a *computation history*, a string describing an entire computation of a Turing machine.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] A CFG can be constructed that generates all strings that are not accepting computation histories for a particular Turing machine on a particular input, and thus it will accept all strings only if the machine does not accept that input.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, do they generate the same language?
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem is a direct consequence of the previous: it is impossible to even decide whether a CFG is equivalent to the trivial CFG defining the language of all strings.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, can the first one generate all strings that the second one can generate?
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] If this problem was decidable, then language equality could be decided too: two CFGs $G_{1}$ and $G_{2}$ generate the same language if $L(G_{1})$ is a subset of $L(G_{2})$ and $L(G_{2})$ is a subset of $L(G_{1})$ .
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The undecidability of this problem follows from the fact that if an algorithm to determine ambiguity existed, the Post correspondence problem could be decided, which is known to be undecidable.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Given two CFGs, is there any string derivable from both grammars?
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Then the PCP instance given by $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{N},\beta _{1},\ldots ,\beta _{N}$ has a solution if and only if ⁠ $L(G_{1})$ ⁠ and ⁠ $L(G_{2})$ ⁠ share a derivable string.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] The left of the string (before the b ) will represent the top of the solution for the PCP instance while the right side will be the bottom in reverse.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] An obvious way to extend the context-free grammar formalism is to allow nonterminals to have arguments, the values of which are passed along within the rules.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] This allows natural language features such as agreement and reference, and programming language analogs such as the correct use and definition of identifiers, to be expressed in a natural way.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] E.g. we can now easily express that in English sentences, the subject and verb must agree in number.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] In computer science, examples of this approach include affix grammars, attribute grammars, indexed grammars, and Van Wijngaarden two-level grammars.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Similar extensions exist in linguistics.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] An **extended context-free grammar** (or **regular right part grammar**) is one in which the right-hand side of the production rules is allowed to be a regular expression over the grammar's terminals and nonterminals.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Extended context-free grammars describe exactly the context-free languages.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Another extension is to allow additional terminal symbols to appear at the left-hand side of rules, constraining their application.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] This produces the formalism of context-sensitive grammars.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] LR parsing extends LL parsing to support a larger range of grammars; in turn, generalized LR parsing extends LR parsing to support arbitrary context-free grammars.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] On LL grammars and LR grammars, it essentially performs LL parsing and LR parsing, respectively, while on nondeterministic grammars, it is as efficient as can be expected.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Although GLR parsing was developed in the 1980s, many new language definitions and parser generators continue to be based on LL, LALR or LR parsing up to the present day.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Chomsky initially hoped to overcome the limitations of context-free grammars by adding transformation rules.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Such rules are another standard device in traditional linguistics; e.g. passivization in English.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Much of generative grammar has been devoted to finding ways of refining the descriptive mechanisms of phrase-structure grammar and transformation rules such that exactly the kinds of things can be expressed that natural language actually allows.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Allowing arbitrary transformations does not meet that goal: they are much too powerful, being Turing complete unless significant restrictions are added (e.g. no transformations that introduce and then rewrite symbols in a context-free fashion).
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Chomsky's general position regarding the non-context-freeness of natural language has held up since then, although his specific examples regarding the inadequacy of context-free grammars in terms of their weak generative capacity were later disproved.
[src:structured-generation/context-free-grammar] Gerald Gazdar and Geoffrey Pullum have argued that despite a few non-context-free constructions in natural language (such as cross-serial dependencies in Swiss German and reduplication in Bambara), the vast majority of forms in natural language are indeed context-free.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A **formal grammar** is a set of symbols and the production rules for rewriting some of them into every possible string of a formal language over an alphabet.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A grammar does not describe the meaning of the strings—only their form.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] In applied mathematics, formal language theory is the discipline that studies formal grammars and languages.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Its applications are found in theoretical computer science, theoretical linguistics, formal semantics, mathematical logic, and other areas.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A formal grammar is a set of rules for rewriting strings, along with a "start symbol" from which rewriting starts.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Therefore, a grammar is usually thought of as a language generator.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] However, it can also be used as the basis for a parser—a function in computing that determines whether a given string belongs to the language or is grammatically incorrect.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] To describe such parsers, formal language theory uses separate formalisms, known as automata theory.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] One result of automata theory is that it is not possible to design a recognizer for certain formal languages.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Many languages have the meanings of their strings structured according to their syntax—a practice known as compositional semantics.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] In these cases, the first step to describing the meaning of a string is to break it down part by part and look at its analyzed form (known as its parse tree in computer science, and as its deep structure in generative grammar).
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A grammar mainly consists of a set of *production rules*, rewrite rules for transforming strings.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Each rule specifies a replacement of a particular string (its *left-hand side*) with another (its *right-hand side*).
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A rule can be applied to each string that contains its left-hand side and produces a string in which an occurrence of that left-hand side has been replaced with its right-hand side.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Unlike a semi-Thue system, which is wholly defined by these rules, a grammar further distinguishes between two kinds of symbols: *nonterminal* and *terminal* symbols; each left-hand side must contain at least one nonterminal symbol.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] It also distinguishes a special nonterminal symbol, called the *start symbol*.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] The language generated by the grammar is defined to be the set of all strings without any nonterminal symbols that can be generated from the string consisting of a single start symbol by (possibly repeated) application of its rules in whatever way possible.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] If there are essentially different ways of generating the same single string, the grammar is said to be ambiguous.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] In the following examples, the terminal symbols are *a* and *b*, and the start symbol is *S*.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] then we start with *S*, and can choose a rule to apply to it.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] If we choose rule 1, we obtain the string *aSb*.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] If we then choose rule 1 again, we replace *S* with *aSb* and obtain the string *aaSbb*.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] If we now choose rule 2, we replace *S* with *ba* and obtain the string *aababb*, and are done.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] We can write this series of choices more briefly, using symbols: $S\Rightarrow aSb\Rightarrow aaSbb\Rightarrow aababb$ .
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] The language of the grammar is the infinite set $\{a^{n}bab^{n}\mid n\geq 0\}=\{ba,abab,aababb,aaababbb,\dotsc \}$ , where $a^{k}$ is a repeated k times (and n in particular represents the number of times production rule 1 has been applied).
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] This grammar is context-free (only single nonterminals appear as left-hand sides) and unambiguous.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] This grammar is not context-free due to rule 3 and it is ambiguous due to the multiple ways in which rule 2 can be used to generate sequences of S s.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] However, the language it generates is simply the set of all nonempty strings consisting of a s and/or b s.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] This is easy to see: to generate a b from an S , use rule 2 twice to generate $SSS$ , then rule 1 twice and rule 3 once to produce b .
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] This means we can generate arbitrary nonempty sequences of S s and then replace each of them with a or b as we please.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] That is, each production rule maps from one string of symbols to another, where the first string (the "head") contains an arbitrary number of symbols provided at least one of them is a nonterminal.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A grammar is formally defined as the tuple $(N,\Sigma ,P,S)$ .
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Such a formal grammar is often called a rewriting system or a phrase structure grammar in the literature.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] This grammar defines the language $L(G)=\left\{a^{n}b^{n}c^{n}\mid n\geq 1\right\}$ where $a^{n}$ denotes a string of *n* consecutive a 's.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Thus, the language is the set of strings that consist of 1 or more a 's, followed by the same number of b 's, followed by the same number of c 's.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] When Noam Chomsky first formalized generative grammars in 1956, he classified them into types now known as the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] The difference between these types is that they have increasingly strict production rules and can therefore express fewer formal languages.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Two important types are *context-free grammars* (Type 2) and *regular grammars* (Type 3).
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] The languages that can be described with such a grammar are called *context-free languages* and *regular languages*, respectively.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Although much less powerful than unrestricted grammars (Type 0), which can in fact express any language that can be accepted by a Turing machine, these two restricted types of grammars are most often used because parsers for them can be efficiently implemented.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] For example, all regular languages can be recognized by a finite-state machine, and for useful subsets of context-free grammars there are well-known algorithms to generate efficient LL parsers and LR parsers to recognize the corresponding languages those grammars generate.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A *context-free grammar* is a grammar in which the left-hand side of each production rule consists of only a single nonterminal symbol.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] This restriction is non-trivial; not all languages can be generated by context-free grammars.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Those that can are called *context-free languages*.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A context-free language can be recognized in $O(n^{3})$ time (*see* Big O notation) by an algorithm such as Earley's recogniser and in a sub-cubic time by fast matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] That is, for every context-free language, a machine can be built that takes a string as input and determines in $O(n^{3})$ time whether the string is a member of the language, where n is the length of the string.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Deterministic context-free languages is a subset of context-free languages that can be recognized in linear time.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] There exist various algorithms that target either this set of languages or some subset of it.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] In regular grammars, the left hand side is again only a single nonterminal symbol, but now the right-hand side is also restricted.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] The right side may be the empty string, or a single terminal symbol, or a single terminal symbol followed by a nonterminal symbol, but nothing else.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] All languages generated by a regular grammar can be recognized in $O(n)$ time by a finite-state machine.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Although in practice, regular grammars are commonly expressed using regular expressions, some forms of regular expression used in practice do not strictly generate the regular languages and do not show linear recognitional performance due to those deviations.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Many extensions and variations on Chomsky's original hierarchy of formal grammars have been developed, both by linguists and by computer scientists, usually either in order to increase their expressive power or in order to make them easier to analyze or parse.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] A recursive grammar is a grammar that contains production rules that are recursive.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] For example, a grammar for a context-free language is left-recursive if there exists a non-terminal symbol *A* that can be put through the production rules to produce a string with *A* as the leftmost symbol.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] An example of recursive grammar is a clause within a sentence separated by two commas.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] All types of grammars in the Chomsky hierarchy can be recursive.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Though there is a tremendous body of literature on parsing algorithms, most of these algorithms assume that the language to be parsed is initially *described* by means of a *generative* formal grammar, and that the goal is to transform this generative grammar into a working parser.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] Strictly speaking, a generative grammar does not in any way correspond to the algorithm used to parse a language, and various algorithms have different restrictions on the form of production rules that are considered well-formed.
[src:structured-generation/formal-grammar] An alternative approach is to formalize the language in terms of an analytic grammar in the first place, which more directly corresponds to the structure and semantics of a parser for the language.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:structured-generation/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:structured-generation/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:structured-generation/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:structured-generation/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:structured-generation/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:structured-generation/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:structured-generation/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:structured-generation/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:structured-generation/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:structured-generation/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:structured-generation/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:structured-generation/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:structured-generation/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:structured-generation/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:structured-generation/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:structured-generation/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:structured-generation/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:structured-generation/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:structured-generation/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:structured-generation/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:structured-generation/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:structured-generation/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:structured-generation/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:structured-generation/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:structured-generation/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:structured-generation/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:structured-generation/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:structured-generation/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:structured-generation/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:structured-generation/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:structured-generation/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:structured-generation/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:structured-generation/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:structured-generation/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:structured-generation/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:structured-generation/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:structured-generation/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:structured-generation/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:structured-generation/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:structured-generation/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:structured-generation/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:structured-generation/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:structured-generation/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:structured-generation/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:structured-generation/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:structured-generation/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:structured-generation/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:structured-generation/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:structured-generation/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:structured-generation/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:structured-generation/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:structured-generation/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:structured-generation/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:structured-generation/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:structured-generation/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:structured-generation/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:structured-generation/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:structured-generation/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:structured-generation/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:structured-generation/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:structured-generation/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:structured-generation/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:structured-generation/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:structured-generation/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:structured-generation/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:structured-generation/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:structured-generation/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:structured-generation/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:structured-generation/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:structured-generation/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:structured-generation/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:structured-generation/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:structured-generation/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:structured-generation/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:structured-generation/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:structured-generation/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:structured-generation/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:structured-generation/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:structured-generation/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:structured-generation/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:structured-generation/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:structured-generation/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:structured-generation/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:structured-generation/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:structured-generation/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:structured-generation/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:structured-generation/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:structured-generation/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:structured-generation/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:structured-generation/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:structured-generation/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
